<paragraph blockId="28.[264,1324,532,998]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
I have remounted a cotype female of this species and designated it the 
<typeStatus box="[1123,1290,532,558]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">LECTOTYPE</typeStatus>
in order to stablise its nomenclature. It is very badly bleached. However, a serious of critical measurements of it and of the 
<typeStatus box="[620,723,612,638]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[762,889,612,637]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Chonocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccata">
<emphasis box="[762,889,612,637]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. buccata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
serve to support Borgmeier’s (
<number box="[1253,1314,612,638]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="1963.0">1963</number>
) synonymy of 
<taxonomicName box="[429,558,652,677]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Chonocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccata">
<emphasis box="[429,558,652,677]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. buccata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with this species. Previously he had altered the ending of Malloch’s name, to 
<taxonomicName box="[450,588,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Chonocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccatus">
<emphasis box="[450,588,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. buccatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(despite this it was then altered to 
<taxonomicName box="[997,1129,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Chonocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccalis">
<emphasis box="[997,1129,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">C. buccalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Bohart).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[264,1324,532,998]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[312,525,732,758]" pageId="28" pageNumber="34" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1935) Sobre o cyclo evolutivo de Chonocephalus Wandolleck e uma nova especie de Melaloncha Brues, endoparasita de abelhas, Archivos do Instituto de Biologia Vegetal, Rio de Janeiro, 2, 255 - 65." type="journal article" year="1935">
Borgmeier (
<number box="[455,516,732,758]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="1935.0">1935</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
correctly pointed out that 
<bibRefCitation author="Brues" box="[844,1014,732,758]" pageId="28" pageNumber="34" refString="Brues, C. T. (1915 a) A new wingless phorid fly from Jamaica, Psyche, 22, 102 - 104." type="journal article" year="1915" yearSuffix="a">
Brues (
<number box="[931,992,732,758]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="1915.0">1915</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
had been incorrect to say that there are no frontal bristles above the antennal cavities. Malloch’s 
<typeStatus box="[1126,1177,772,798]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">type</typeStatus>
series comprised five females. 
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier" box="[500,711,812,838]" pageId="28" pageNumber="34" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1963) Revision of the North American phorid flies. Part I. The Phorinae, Aenigmatiinae and Metopininae, except Megaselia (Diptera, Phoridae), Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 6, 1 - 256." type="journal article" year="1963">
Borgmeier (
<number box="[641,702,812,838]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="1963.0">1963</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
stated that he had one 
<typeStatus box="[977,1078,812,838]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">paratype</typeStatus>
in his collection, but subsequently lost it. Furthermore he retracted his previous (
<number box="[971,1032,852,878]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="1935.0">1935</number>
) statement that the hairs at the rear of the abdominal tergites arose from pale spots. However, I have remounted on slides the 
<typeStatus box="[384,486,932,958]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">holotype</typeStatus>
in the 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" box="[572,657,932,958]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">USNM</collectionCode>
and a 
<typeStatus box="[739,840,932,958]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">paratype</typeStatus>
in the MKB. This species has such pale spots, but they are sometimes only slightly paler than the rest of the tergite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
